{"success": true, "message": "Fetched question.", "data": {"showTimer": true, "showAttemptInsight": true, "playSounds": true, "dontShowCorrectAnswerImmediately": false, "_id": "648b5a6d417cc3fb48d67add", "classes": [], "exams": ["615d76b2c52ffa3c944600df"], "subjects": ["615d70bd9948bc1b21da2b1f"], "chapters": ["615d6fee2b295b085ab6ebb5"], "topics": [], "concepts": [], "previousYearPapers": [{"_id": "63134c746e7bc9b332483705", "title": "JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 1)", "isVisible": true}], "type": "singleCorrect", "level": 2, "approximateTimeRequired": 120, "question": {"text": "<p>Given below are two statements:</p><p>Statement I : The chlorides of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Be</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Al</mi></math> have Cl-bridged structure. Both are soluble in organic solvents and act as Lewis bases.</p><p>Statement II: Hydroxides of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Be</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Al</mi></math> dissolve in excess alkali to give beryllate and aluminate ions. In the light of the above statements. Choose the correct answer from the options given below.</p>", "image": null}, "options": [{"id": "OB4Sg", "text": "Both statement I and Statement II are true", "isCorrect": false, "image": null}, {"id": "w3Brc", "text": "Both statement I and Statement II are false", "isCorrect": false, "image": null}, {"id": "NA57F", "text": "Statement I is true but Statement II is false", "isCorrect": false, "image": null}, {"id": "JukqD", "text": "Statement I is false but Statement II is true", "isCorrect": true, "image": null}], "correctValue": null, "solution": {"text": "<blockquote><p>The chlorides of both beryllium and aluminium have Cl&ndash; bridged chloride structure in vapour phase. Both the chlorides are soluble in organic solvents and are strong Lewis acids. They are used as Friedel Craft catalysts.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Be</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> is lewis acid and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math> has complete octet.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Be</mi></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Al</mi></math> are amphoteric metals therefore dissolve in acid as well as alkaline solution and form beryllate and aluminate ions in excess alkali.</p><p>&nbsp;Beryllium hydroxide dissolves in excess of alkali to give a beryllate ion,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Be</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mo>]</mo><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#8211;</mo></mrow></msup></math> just as aluminium hydroxide gives aluminate ion, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Al</mi><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>4</mn></msub><msup><mo>]</mo><mo>-</mo></msup></math></p></blockquote>", "image": null}, "videoSolution": null, "questionLabels": [], "masterId": "MOGJMPYQ51669823", "source": "EM", "bucket": "Must Do Ques (JEE Main) - Any Difficulty", "numericalLowerLimit": null, "numericalUpperLimit": null, "category": null, "microConcepts": [], "imageBaseUrl": null, "helperText": null, "isRemoved": false, "cpyqbSubjects": ["615f0cf69476412f48314dac", "616057040283de43c87e3e16", "61bb58281213731910ea0b71", "6160579d0283de43c87e3e1f", "61964f94a5a526011886801e", "61c055f6e8ce0dc8a5c62d34", "61a8a2cce8ce0dc8a5c62d2e", "6160577e0283de43c87e3e1c", "616057210283de43c87e3e19", "629105adee9e3ae00d63352c", "62962075e7f8e9ac4daeafd8", "629f385f263330a77be9fa7e", "629f39e4ac11b26562e0625c", "61964ff3a5a5260118868022", "64d50c263df7f4a7f3017f70", "